{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## What\n\nAdd intent-based navigation so each audience (human client, LLM client, human\ncontributor, LLM contributor) reaches the right doc fast, plus a compact\nsymptom→recovery troubleshooting table for the most common failure modes.\n\n## Scope\n- Add a short \"Choose your path\" router near the top of `docs/README.md` routing by\n  intent, e.g. \"Start using rebar\", \"Drive rebar over MCP\", \"Contribute a code\n  change\", \"Understand the internals\".\n- Add a compact troubleshooting table mapping common symptoms to specific fixes, e.g.\n  \"claim/transition exits 10\" → optimistic-concurrency, pick another ticket;\n  \"`rebar-mcp` missing\" → install the `[mcp]` extra; \"`unknown key … ignored`\" →\n  stale global build, use the repo venv. Keep it small; expand on demand.\n\nKeep the router and table concise — this is a routing aid, not a second manual.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `docs/README.md` opens with a short intent router covering the four audiences.\n- [ ] A troubleshooting table maps at least the three symptoms above to concrete\n      recovery steps with links.\n- [ ] Every router/table link resolves (verified locally with the link checker; the\n      docs-index / link CI gate added by sibling `f088` then keeps it enforced — this\n      ticket does not require `f088` to pre-exist).\n\nFiles: `docs/README.md`."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783816776190995001,"uuid":"ad6a963f-78fe-4a31-8dfa-1f0c382f099f"}